    <section class="card">
      <h1>About Student Evidence App</h1>

      <p>
        Student Evidence App helps teachers review student writing progress by recording drafting evidence such as paste events, declarations, references, citations, draft history and teacher-reviewed feedback.
      </p>

      <p>
        The app is designed as a teacher-support tool. It does not make final academic integrity decisions, misconduct findings, or final grades. Teachers remain responsible for reviewing evidence, applying school policy, and making professional judgements.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Educational Purpose</h2>

      <p>
        The app supports transparent writing, source acknowledgement, drafting practice, responsible AI use, and student reflection. This aligns with Australian Curriculum Technologies and Digital Literacy expectations around data security, privacy, ethical use of digital systems, online safety, and responsible digital identity management.
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>Students can show evidence of drafting and source use.</li>
        <li>Teachers can review writing development over time.</li>
        <li>Declarations help students explain pasted, referenced, or AI-assisted material.</li>
        <li>AI feedback is teacher-controlled and should be reviewed before use.</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="small">
        ACARA’s Technologies learning area includes data security and ethical/legal considerations when designing digital systems. Its Digital Literacy capability includes managing digital privacy and identity. 
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Queensland and Federal Privacy Considerations</h2>

      <p>
        The app should be used with school approval and in line with school privacy, information management, data retention, and ICT policies.
      </p>

      <h3>Recommended school controls</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Use only with approved classes and a clear educational purpose.</li>
        <li>Collect only the student data needed for writing evidence and feedback.</li>
        <li>Limit teacher/admin access to authorised staff.</li>
        <li>Tell students what evidence is collected and why.</li>
        <li>Do not use AI outputs as final decisions.</li>
        <li>Set a clear data retention and deletion process.</li>
        <li>Review hosting, database location, backups, and access controls with school IT.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Queensland Department of Education privacy and information management guidance covers collection, storage, use, transfer, disclosure and protection of personal information and information assets. The Australian Privacy Principles under the Privacy Act 1988 set privacy obligations for covered organisations and agencies. 
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>AI Use Statement</h2>

      <p>
        The app may use AI to draft teacher feedback against a rubric or ISMG. AI feedback is provided as a draft only. A teacher must review, edit, and approve any feedback before it is used with students.
      </p>

      <p>
        The app should not send unnecessary personal information to an AI service. Where possible, use initials or minimal identifiers, and avoid sensitive personal information.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Copyright and Referencing</h2>

      <p>
        Students are expected to acknowledge sources used in their work. The app includes declaration, citation, and bibliography tools to support this.
      </p>

      <p>
        School use of third-party material should comply with Australian copyright law, school copyright procedures, statutory education licences, and attribution requirements. Queensland Department of Education copyright guidance states that third-party copyright materials used for educational purposes should be attributed, even when permission is not required.
      </p>

      <h3>Student expectations</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Declare copied or pasted source material.</li>
        <li>Reference websites, books, articles, videos, teacher resources, and AI tools where required.</li>
        <li>Use quoted or copied material appropriately.</li>
        <li>Do not submit AI-generated material as unaided personal work unless permitted by the task rules.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Important Disclaimer</h2>

      <p>
        This page is general information for school review and is not legal advice. Schools should check their own policies, parent/student consent requirements, privacy notices, data processing arrangements, copyright procedures, and ICT security expectations before wider rollout.
      </p>

